🏄‍♀️TRAVEL STORY // Is this even real life?

Journal entry | September 11, 2022

We surfed this crystal blue barrelling left this morning. Just us. 

It was I think the clearest water I’ve ever experienced. I could see the colours of the corals with my bare eyes, the channels in the reef. 

The way this wave was peeling, you could almost hear it whistle. sssssssssss

Not a single building in sight along the whole coast line. Kilometers of jungle stretching over mountains in the backdrop. Unbelievable that this is even part of the same planet as the pines and icy lands I’m from.

Oh and yesterday? As the sun was setting on the water on one side, a gigantic double rainbow got drawn on the other. The colourful arc appeared so close, that it felt like we could almost touch it. 

I stretched my arms up.

Turtles came popping their heads out. 

Everyone was bathing in the golden hour light. Unreal, but real. 

I took mental pictures click.click. 

Trying to encapsulate the show Mother Earth was putting on.

Wish you could see it too.

How much more beauty than chaos

There is down under.

One year ago 🎞️ I always get this strange bittersweet feeling looking back at these pictures from the trip to Maldives & Sumatra.

I look at my smile, and think: Gawd, she didn’t know yet — or maybe she kinda did, but surely didn’t know how to move through it yet…

⏮️ At the same time last year in August, about to embark on this big trip, I felt physically unwell but couldn't figure out the why. Counterintuitively, I chose to go on the trip anyway. I’ve always wanted a taste of everything, and missing it had one of failure I couldn’t bare.

We spent 6 weeks chasing some of the best waves on Earth with friends that felt like family. Some moments and views we experienced in the water live with me forever. It was a rare adventure.✨

I had to be on this trip, and I know why:

I fell super ill in the middle of buttfock faraway lands, and ended up hospitalized in Indonesia where they determined I wasn’t ‘fit to fly’ temporarily.

Forced to stop and experiencing my own fragility, new perspectives emerged.

I was catapulted into a new season of my life — a metaphorical Winter. A season of transition, of shedding skin, of realigning the angle + speed of the ship.

Just as we observe in nature, some parts must die to in the metamorphosis; it’s a necessary cycle.

Yesterday, @joshlynott sent me some pieces from the book ‘Wintering’, and it felt like a balm and one more validation of what I went through. 

And then I realized, I’m slowly Springing 🌸🌷🌼. I remember very well what last August felt like, unable to bike, run, surf without a pain in the chest — and the post-hospital months feeling like a baby giraffe who couldn’t trust her legs.

I am amazed — I look at my reflection now and see a strong, graceful and renewed lady.
With a different pace, a different dance.
She is me. 🦋🌞

This is how I’ve learned that 𝙡𝙞𝙛𝙚 𝙞𝙨 𝙖 𝙗𝙖𝙡𝙖𝙣𝙘𝙚 𝙗𝙚𝙩𝙬𝙚𝙚𝙣 𝙢𝙖𝙠𝙞𝙣𝙜 𝙞𝙩 𝙝𝙖𝙥𝙥𝙚𝙣, 𝙖𝙣𝙙 𝙡𝙚𝙩𝙩𝙞𝙣𝙜 𝙞𝙩 𝙝𝙖𝙥𝙥𝙚𝙣.

I don’t miss surfing — I miss the spontaneity of life at the beach.

This year I’ve spent a Guinness World Record time in Canada — which was needed. But I observe how the flow of life is just so different here. Dinners with friends are planned well in advance. You play soccer on Tuesdays. Vacation in July. Sync Google Cal. And we already know we are busy the weekend of the 24th. If I wanna go biking on a Tuesday morning, I don’t know who to call… 
/
Down south, I love living in a small community where you know about everyone by their nickname.
Where “going for sunset” is a legitimate activity.
You walk down the beach, you bump into some friends. No phone no shoes no problem. Always a conversation to be held.
/
I love having breaky at @caneguecafe, seeing Oli, knowing I’ll see my mates and stay for 2h instead of 30.
/
Having my best friend as a neighbour. Roll into her aircon, ask her to play some ukulele to forget a broken heart.
/
Having Amy or Amanda who are always willing to hop on a flight about any day, go to Mexico City or Miami just to gtfo and have a proper wine.
/
Full moon ceremonies.
Impromptu BBQs.
A calm night that turn into a dance off.
Powercuts to intimate candlelit dinner.
A hot shower.
A new stranger with green eyes in town.
/
The sport of surfing is by nature, unpredictable. The playground does its own dance, tides change by 50min everyday — and so is its lifestyle.
Surf mission across the country get organized 1 day ahead.
Nowhere to keep score of your performance. 
You had fun, or you didn’t, and that’s all. 

I love / miss / have chosen to wake up to a life that is ultimately pretty rustic. Far from the words sophisticated, fashionable or technological.
But rather
connected, spontaneous, and playful.

I don’t want us to forget, how to do the mundane in togetherness. How to love, grief, let go, let in, cook as a shared experience. Not alone in our unit, not alone behind a screen. No, we need a village.
/
I miss surfing on a Tuesday with the crew, because it’s pumping and that’s all that matter this morning.

See you soon 🌊🌞

UNCHARTED TERRITORIES 🦜🌿 Got back to El Salvador with a mission: I wanted to find running trails, which is not a very comon activity at the beach. You either surf, or you are here for Bitcoins, basically.

- Can you ride?! He asked.
- Yes, I rode the big bikes twice…
- Perfect, let’s get on the bikes tomorrow, we’ll find you some running trails!

yesss lfg!!!

Finally, we caught sunset on a ridge they call ‘South Siberia’. 🌅Full speed on the open road on the way back. Largest smile.

Ya girl now got some running trails AND wants an electric dirt bike!!! Haha!

How does one even begin to write about death. The ink of my pen have been dry for the last 6 weeks. I’m a woman of words and yet, I felt unable to align few of them. Sensing I needed to first take a step back to feel the download. But maybe that’s exactly the thing about death, is that it never really leaves you. Something breaks, and shifts, and becomes forever unfixable. It’s accepting that an unfinished story is finished. And this case, that his son will never remember his daddy. This truth hardly lands. It’s unimaginable that life can be so fragile. And yet it is.

Death demands us to hold ambivalent truths in our head, in our heart.
Remember, and yet let go.
To hold still, and let grow.
Life altering, and yet seeing life goes on.
Feel surrounded, yet lonely.
Grieve, and welcome joy…
Confusing for the ones who go on living.
But we never get over great loss, it carves us into more compassionate beings. The hole doesn’t shrink — life eventually starts to grow bigger around it.
A new sense of normal, a new reality and vision is slowly created. But first, everything you once understood as established, vaporizes.

There are two truths that have emerged for me.
A) Our trip on Earth is short. Shorter than we like to believe.
B) We need each other. And I don’t say that lightly; we really frickin’ need each other.

This visit to Ecuador wasn’t planned, and turned out to be one of the most important trip of my life. The power of community and unicity we’ve experience the last month is like nothing I lived before. Sad. Rich. Hard. Full. Slow. Fast. All of it.

When I was younger, someone asked me :
Who would carry a dead body with you?
This question really left a mark on me.
Over the years, the multiple hellos & goodbyes that come with the type of lifestyle we’ve chosen, often left me wondering.
Wondering who would… ?!
I feel different now, I feel like I know better.
At least I know who I would personally do it for.

I love you @marieamyot 🤍✨
